Shikwa is chapter 20 of Bang-e-Dara Part 3. The Spain reference appears in two consecutive stanzas of the poem's central boast section: first, the speaker claims Muslims called the adhan "in Europe's churches" (p-e1af7a), and then the clincher — "in the Sea of Darkness, rode our horses, wild and free" (p-56fa40). *Bahr-e-Zulmat* (Sea of Darkness) is the classical Urdu/Persian term for the Atlantic Ocean, and the image of riding horses into it is Iqbal's allusion to the Muslim conquest of al-Andalus — the armies that crossed the Strait of Gibraltar and pressed all the way to the Atlantic shore.
